<i>The American people</i>
<i>need to know the truth,</i>

207
00:11:36,429 --> 00:11:39,660
<i>and I don't think</i>
<i>it will ever now</i>
<i>be fully known.</i>

208
00:12:02,788 --> 00:12:05,621
<i>So how do we want to
address the college protests?</i>

209
00:12:05,691 --> 00:12:06,885
Well, do we want
to lift some quotes

210
00:12:06,959 --> 00:12:10,087
from the "stand up
and be counted" speech
in 1970?

211
00:12:10,162 --> 00:12:11,789
- Sir?
- <i>You know, maybe we're just better off</i>

212
00:12:11,864 --> 00:12:13,388
using the whole
Lincoln Memorial memo.

213
00:12:13,466 --> 00:12:14,933
<i>Just include
the whole thing.</i>

214
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,468
Mr. President,
Swifty Lazar is here.

215
00:12:17,536 --> 00:12:19,800
Okay. No, no, stick around.

216
00:12:19,872 --> 00:12:22,067
You're gonna get
a kick out of this.

217
00:12:22,141 --> 00:12:25,372
This is my literary agent
from Hollywood.

218
00:12:25,444 --> 00:12:27,639
Hygiene obsessive.

219
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:33,109
Mr. President,
good to see you.

220
00:12:33,185 --> 00:12:34,812
Nice to see you.

221
00:12:34,887 --> 00:12:37,481
These are folks
helping me with my book.

222
00:12:37,556 --> 00:12:40,457
Diane Sawyer,
Frank Gannon,
Irving Lazar.

223
00:12:40,526 --> 00:12:42,084
Nice to meet you.
Miss Sawyer.

224
00:12:42,161 --> 00:12:43,890
Pleasure.
Mr. Gannon.

225
00:12:47,800 --> 00:12:49,825
Okay, that's it.
I'll see you after lunch.

226
00:12:49,902 --> 00:12:51,893
<i>So how you feeling, sir?</i>

227
00:12:52,304 --> 00:12:56,866
I'm better, thank you.
Though not yet
well enough to golf,

228
00:12:57,710 --> 00:13:00,577
thank God.
I despise that game.

229
00:13:01,580 --> 00:13:04,105
Imagine, six weeks
out of office

230
00:13:04,183 --> 00:13:06,708
as President
of the United States,

231
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:09,653
and they'd have me putting
in my hospital room.

232
00:13:09,722 --> 00:13:11,713
Never retire, Mr. Lazar.

233
00:13:12,158 --> 00:13:17,095
To me, the unhappiest
people of the world
are retired.

234
00:13:17,163 --> 00:13:18,960
No purpose.

235
00:13:19,031 --> 00:13:21,795
What makes life mean
something is purpose.

236
00:13:21,867 --> 00:13:24,768
A goal. A battle. A struggle.

237
00:13:24,837 --> 00:13:27,067
Well, even if
you don't win it.

238
00:13:27,573 --> 00:13:30,064
When my doctor
declared me unfit

239
00:13:30,142 --> 00:13:31,973
to give testimony
in the Watergate trial,

240
00:13:32,044 --> 00:13:34,274
everybody thought
I'd be relieved.

241
00:13:34,346 --> 00:13:35,938
Well, they were wrong.

242
00:13:36,015 --> 00:13:37,539
That was the lowest I got.

243
00:13:37,616 --> 00:13:42,053
Well, if it's a challenge
you want, here's one
you might enjoy.

244
00:13:42,121 --> 00:13:46,057
How to spend $2 million,
2.3 to be precise.

245
00:13:46,125 --> 00:13:47,922
It's what I got
for your memoirs.

246
00:13:47,993 --> 00:13:49,460
Well, thank you.

247
00:13:49,528 --> 00:13:50,790
Eh...

248
00:13:50,863 --> 00:13:52,626
It might be a little short
of what I wanted,

249
00:13:52,698 --> 00:13:56,259
but let me assure you,
it's a whole lot more
than they wanted.

250
00:13:56,335 --> 00:13:58,360
That book is important to me.

251
00:13:58,437 --> 00:14:02,134
It's probably the only
chance I'm gonna get
to put the record straight

252
00:14:02,208 --> 00:14:05,575
and remind people
the Nixon years
weren't all bad.

253
00:14:07,046 --> 00:14:10,948
You know, if you're trying
to put the record straight,

254
00:14:11,016 --> 00:14:12,483
I'd at least talk to him.

255
00:14:12,551 --> 00:14:13,677
<i>Who?</i>

256
00:14:14,119 --> 00:14:17,452
David Frost.
English talk show guy.

257
00:14:18,190 --> 00:14:21,091
Why would I want to
talk to David Frost?

258
00:14:21,160 --> 00:14:23,958
Well, a while back,
he wrote asking
for an interview.

259
00:14:24,029 --> 00:14:25,360
No.

260
00:14:25,431 --> 00:14:26,762
Well, we didn't
get back to him.

261
00:14:26,832 --> 00:14:29,164
Frankly, we didn't
find him appropriate.

262
00:14:29,235 --> 00:14:31,999
Well, I thought
that we were
doing one with CBS.

263
00:14:32,071 --> 00:14:34,039
We are. I just figured
doing it with Frost

264
00:14:34,106 --> 00:14:36,233
would be a whole lot
easier than doing it
with Mike Wallace.

265
00:14:36,308 --> 00:14:40,642
It would, but it would
have a lot less,
you know, credibility.

266
00:14:40,713 --> 00:14:44,240
True, true. Could
probably get more money.

267
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:48,815
Really?
Look.

268
00:14:48,888 --> 00:14:52,289
We'll always have
350 on the table
from CBS.

269
00:14:52,358 --> 00:14:56,089
But if I could get
Frost to pay more
and secure better terms,

270
00:14:56,595 --> 00:14:58,688
it might be a shame to pass.

271
00:14:59,265 --> 00:15:02,462
It'd be interesting to know
where he is right now.

272
00:15:02,902 --> 00:15:05,496
We tied him to
railway tracks,
and he escaped.

273
00:15:06,038 --> 00:15:08,836
We buried him alive,
and he walked free.

274
00:15:08,908 --> 00:15:13,311
Today we're lowering
escape artist Derek Harrison
into the water

275
00:15:13,379 --> 00:15:17,713
to see if he can
miraculously
cheat death once more.

276
00:15:17,783 --> 00:15:20,217
Good evening,
and welcome to
<i>Great Escapes.</i>

277
00:15:20,286 --> 00:15:22,220
My name is David Frost.

278
00:15:24,256 --> 00:15:25,848
<i>Okay, that is a cut.</i>

279
00:15:25,925 --> 00:15:27,017
Thank you.

280
00:15:27,092 --> 00:15:30,391
In any deal, you need to
know your opponent's
breaking point.

281
00:15:31,797 --> 00:15:33,492
To assess that,
you might call them

282
00:15:33,565 --> 00:15:35,795
late at night
or at the weekend.

283
00:15:36,435 --> 00:15:39,268
If they take the call,
you know they're desperate.

284
00:15:39,338 --> 00:15:42,774
And from that moment on,
you know you have
the upper hand.

285
00:15:53,852 --> 00:15:55,012
Hello?

286
00:15:55,087 --> 00:15:56,782
<i>Mr. Frost? Irving Lazar.</i>

287
00:15:58,157 --> 00:15:59,647
Who?

288
00:15:59,725 --> 00:16:02,888
Swifty Lazar.
I represent
President Nixon.

289
00:16:02,962 --> 00:16:04,224
What time is it?

290
00:16:04,296 --> 00:16:05,285
<i>Bad time?</i>

291
00:16:05,364 --> 00:16:08,162
No! Not at all.

292
00:16:11,236 --> 00:16:15,070
I'm calling with regard to
your request for an interview

293
00:16:15,140 --> 00:16:18,132
and to say,
having considered it,

294
00:16:18,210 --> 00:16:22,203
my client is not necessarily
opposed to the idea.

295
00:16:22,281 --> 00:16:26,012
Really?
Well, that's terrific news!

296
00:16:26,085 --> 00:16:27,814
For God's sake.

297
00:16:27,886 --> 00:16:29,945
<i>I got $500,000.</i>

298
00:16:30,022 --> 00:16:31,421
Is that good?

299
00:16:31,490 --> 00:16:36,120
Mr. President, it's a half a
million dollars for a news interview.

300
00:16:36,195 --> 00:16:37,457
It's unprecedented.

301
00:16:37,529 --> 00:16:39,724
Yeah? Well, what's the catch?

302
00:16:39,798 --> 00:16:42,961
<i>With Frost? None.</i>
<i>It'll be a big wet kiss.</i>

303
00:16:43,535 --> 00:16:46,163
This guy'll be so grateful
to be getting it at all,

304
00:16:46,238 --> 00:16:47,933
he'll pitch
puffballs all night

305
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,840
and pay a half a million
dollars for the privilege.

306
00:16:54,213 --> 00:16:56,579
Well, you think
you could get 550?

307
00:16:57,883 --> 00:16:59,214
I got 6.

308
00:17:00,919 --> 00:17:02,784
- David, how could you have done that?
- What?

309
00:17:02,855 --> 00:17:04,789
$600,000. That's a fortune.

310
00:17:04,857 --> 00:17:05,846
200 on signature?

311
00:17:05,924 --> 00:17:07,391
Don't worry about the money.

312
00:17:07,459 --> 00:17:09,825
My God.
Most Americans think
he belongs in jail.

313
00:17:09,895 --> 00:17:11,590
You're making him
a rich man.

314
00:17:11,663 --> 00:17:13,597
Plus, by outbidding them,
you've already made enemies

315
00:17:13,665 --> 00:17:15,155
of the networks.
They're just jealous.

316
00:17:15,234 --> 00:17:17,759
They're already sounding off
about checkbook journalism.

317
00:17:17,836 --> 00:17:19,269
And if the networks
are against you,

318
00:17:19,338 --> 00:17:20,737
syndication's always
going to be a struggle.

319
00:17:20,806 --> 00:17:22,364
No syndication,
no advance sales.

320
00:17:22,441 --> 00:17:23,965
No advance sales,
no commercials.

321
00:17:24,043 --> 00:17:25,476
No commercials, no revenue.

322
00:17:25,544 --> 00:17:29,207
And here's the bigger
question, why do it?
You don't need it.

323
00:17:29,281 --> 00:17:30,407
Your career's
in great shape.

324
00:17:30,482 --> 00:17:32,643
This will just spread you
across three continents,

325
00:17:32,718 --> 00:17:34,310
jeopardize the other shows.

326
00:17:34,386 --> 00:17:35,785
Isn't it true that
Channel Nine in Australia

327
00:17:35,854 --> 00:17:37,549
want you to do
another season
of your talk show for them?

328
00:17:37,623 --> 00:17:38,681
Yes.
And London, too?

329
00:17:38,757 --> 00:17:40,884
Yes, but that would be
London and Australia.

330
00:17:40,959 --> 00:17:42,722
This would be...
What?

331
00:17:43,328 --> 00:17:44,818
You wouldn't
understand, John.

332
00:17:44,897 --> 00:17:47,730
You were never
part of the show
in New York,

333
00:17:48,367 --> 00:17:50,164
but it's indescribable.

334
00:17:50,235 --> 00:17:55,298
Success in America
is unlike success
anywhere else.

335
00:17:56,742 --> 00:17:58,767
And the emptiness
when it's gone.

336
00:18:00,179 --> 00:18:05,617
And the sickening
thought that it may
never come back.

337
00:18:06,552 --> 00:18:08,918
You know, there's
a restaurant in New York
called Sardi's.

338
00:18:08,987 --> 00:18:10,750
Ordinary mortals
can't get a table.

339
00:18:10,823 --> 00:18:12,518
John, the place
was my canteen!

340
00:18:12,591 --> 00:18:13,683
You know, I'd be happier

341
00:18:13,759 --> 00:18:14,987
if I heard
some kind of vision

342
00:18:15,060 --> 00:18:16,220
that you had
for this interview.

343
00:18:16,295 --> 00:18:17,455
<i>Excuse me, Mr. Frost.

344
00:18:17,529 --> 00:18:18,655
I'd heard you were
going to be here.

345
00:18:18,730 --> 00:18:20,664
Would you mind?
Of course.

346
00:18:20,732 --> 00:18:22,222
But I don't.
I just hear
a man doing it

347
00:18:22,301 --> 00:18:23,563
because it would
create headlines

348
00:18:23,635 --> 00:18:25,728
or give him a place
at the top table.

349
00:18:25,804 --> 00:18:27,169
And that is what
makes me nervous.

350
00:18:27,239 --> 00:18:29,969
And you do nervous
so beautifully, John.

351
00:18:30,042 --> 00:18:33,341
"Hello, good evening
and welcome."

352
00:18:36,548 --> 00:18:38,482
I don't actually say that.

353
00:18:38,550 --> 00:18:40,108
Hello, Mr. Frost.

354
00:18:46,692 --> 00:18:47,920
Champagne?

355
00:18:47,993 --> 00:18:49,688
<i>No, thank you.</i>

356
00:18:50,696 --> 00:18:52,755
<i>Another glass, sir?</i>

357
00:19:10,282 --> 00:19:12,443
You don't like champagne?

358
00:19:13,919 --> 00:19:15,477
Not on airplanes.

359
00:19:15,554 --> 00:19:17,852
Yes, it dehydrates
one terribly.

360
00:19:18,690 --> 00:19:21,352
The trick is to have
a glass of water
on the go, too.

361
00:19:21,426 --> 00:19:23,951
Like the Viennese
serve coffee.

362
00:19:24,029 --> 00:19:26,293
Well, I've never
been to Vienna.

363
00:19:26,365 --> 00:19:28,833
Oh. Well, you'd like it.

364
00:19:28,901 --> 00:19:31,927
It's like Paris
without the French.

365
00:19:34,940 --> 00:19:36,498
What's your name?

366
00:19:36,575 --> 00:19:37,769
Caroline.

367
00:19:37,843 --> 00:19:38,867
David.

368
00:19:38,944 --> 00:19:41,640
Yes, I know. David Frost.

369
00:19:42,648 --> 00:19:45,446
"Hello and good evening
and welcome."

370
00:19:50,189 --> 00:19:53,886
You know, I heard
an interview with you
recently on the radio.

371
00:19:53,959 --> 00:19:56,291
You were giving it
from the back
of your Rolls-Royce.

372
00:19:56,361 --> 00:19:57,487
Bentley.

373
00:19:57,563 --> 00:19:58,621
On the phone.

374
00:19:58,697 --> 00:19:59,959
They said that
you were a person

375
00:20:00,032 --> 00:20:03,058
who defined
the age we live in.

376
00:20:03,135 --> 00:20:04,727
Really?
Mmm.

377
00:20:05,270 --> 00:20:06,862
You and Vidal Sassoon.

378
00:20:08,574 --> 00:20:11,543
But what made you
exceptional, they said,

379
00:20:11,610 --> 00:20:15,546
was that you were a person
who had achieved great fame

380
00:20:15,614 --> 00:20:18,981
without possessing
any discernible quality.

381
00:20:19,051 --> 00:20:20,279
How kind.
Mmm-hmm.

382
00:20:20,352 --> 00:20:23,651
And that you fly
around a great deal.

383
00:20:23,722 --> 00:20:26,020
Well, that's true.

384
00:20:26,925 --> 00:20:27,914
Why?

385
00:20:27,993 --> 00:20:29,483
I like to keep busy.

386
00:20:30,128 --> 00:20:31,527
Why?

387
00:20:31,597 --> 00:20:34,157
I find it
more interesting
than keeping still.

388
00:20:35,234 --> 00:20:37,168
You know,
you have very sad eyes.

389
00:20:37,869 --> 00:20:39,666
Do I?
Mmm.

390
00:20:39,738 --> 00:20:41,729
Has anyone told
you that before?

391
00:20:42,274 --> 00:20:43,536
No.

392
00:20:43,609 --> 00:20:45,270
Are you a sad person?

393
00:20:49,147 --> 00:20:51,707
Let's talk about
you a little bit.

394
00:20:51,783 --> 00:20:54,274
Of course, you feel more
comfortable asking questions.

395
00:20:54,353 --> 00:20:56,287
How right you are!

396
00:20:56,622 --> 00:20:58,351
<i>This is your</i>
<i>captain speaking.</i>

397
00:20:58,423 --> 00:20:59,412
<i>You may have</i>
<i>noticed we've begun</i>

398
00:20:59,491 --> 00:21:01,618
<i>our final descent</i>
<i>into Los Angeles.</i>

399
00:21:02,527 --> 00:21:05,587
<i>If you could please</i>
<i>return to your seats</i>
<i>and fasten your seat belts,</i>

400
00:21:05,664 --> 00:21:07,723
<i>we'll be landing</i>
<i>very shortly. Thank you.</i>

401
00:21:07,799 --> 00:21:10,097
<i>So how about you?
Where are you going?</i>

402
00:21:10,168 --> 00:21:12,534
To meet Richard Nixon.

403
00:21:12,604 --> 00:21:13,832
Really?

404
00:21:15,507 --> 00:21:18,305
You know, they say he has
the most enormous head,

405
00:21:18,777 --> 00:21:20,335
but the sexiest voice.

406
00:21:20,412 --> 00:21:21,777
Where is he now?

407
00:21:22,047 --> 00:21:25,574
In some dark underground cave
licking his wounds?

408
00:21:26,451 --> 00:21:29,215
Actually, no.
In his rather smart beachside villa

409
00:21:29,288 --> 00:21:30,346
in California.

410
00:21:30,422 --> 00:21:33,152
Really? Richard Nixon
in a beachside villa?

411
00:21:33,225 --> 00:21:34,817
How incongruous.

412
00:21:34,893 --> 00:21:36,861
You can come if you'd like.

413
00:21:37,362 --> 00:21:39,023
To meet Nixon?

414
00:21:39,765 --> 00:21:41,460
Why not?

415
00:21:42,834 --> 00:21:44,131
Are you sure?

416
00:21:47,172 --> 00:21:48,867
You know, I would love that.

417
00:21:48,940 --> 00:21:51,101
<i>Cabin crew,</i>
<i>please prepare for arrival.</i>

418
00:21:51,176 --> 00:21:54,043
Well, I'll get
my office to call you
first thing in the morning

419
00:21:54,112 --> 00:21:56,672
and send a car with a phone.

420
00:21:56,748 --> 00:21:57,737
Oh.

421
00:22:00,185 --> 00:22:03,245
He did, too. Money no object.

422
00:22:03,322 --> 00:22:07,315
Everything glittered
and was golden.

423
00:22:07,392 --> 00:22:08,859
Well, on the outside.

424
00:22:08,927 --> 00:22:11,760
<i>Of course, what I didn't know</i>
<i>was that in the meantime,</i>

425
00:22:11,830 --> 00:22:13,991
<i>he'd gone to all</i>
<i>the major networks</i>

426
00:22:14,066 --> 00:22:16,534
<i>to try and get</i>
<i>interest in the interviews.</i>

427
00:22:17,069 --> 00:22:19,936
I'm sorry, David,
but we have a policy

428
00:22:20,005 --> 00:22:22,439
of not paying
for a news interview.

429
00:22:22,507 --> 00:22:25,670
Look, we love your work
as an entertainer.

430
00:22:25,744 --> 00:22:26,870
That <i>Guinness</i> show?

431
00:22:26,945 --> 00:22:28,435
Love it. You're a funny guy.

432
00:22:28,513 --> 00:22:30,708
But an interview like this?

433
00:22:30,782 --> 00:22:33,683
You're asking us to pay
a British talk show host

434
00:22:33,752 --> 00:22:35,982
to interview
an American president

435
00:22:36,054 --> 00:22:39,717
with absolutely no editorial
controls whatsoever in return?

436
00:22:39,791 --> 00:22:41,759
Well, you can't say
it's not a fresh approach.

437
00:22:41,827 --> 00:22:43,556
I know you're very busy.

438
00:22:43,695 --> 00:22:45,629
I'm not gonna
keep you from it.

439
00:22:46,264 --> 00:22:47,856
Thank you for coming in.

440
00:22:47,933 --> 00:22:50,026
I'm gonna have to
get back to you.

441
00:22:50,102 --> 00:22:52,969
Okay, thank you so
much for your time.

442
00:22:53,038 --> 00:22:54,096
David, good luck.

443
00:22:54,172 --> 00:22:56,538
He never let on
to anyone at the time,

444
00:22:56,608 --> 00:22:57,802
not even me.
You know,
that would have meant...

445
00:22:58,710 --> 00:22:59,699
Thanks.

446
00:22:59,778 --> 00:23:03,339
...<i>admitting failure,</i>
<i>and David doesn't do failure.</i>

447
00:23:34,446 --> 00:23:36,380
<i>There you are.</i>

448
00:23:36,448 --> 00:23:38,939
See, you don't have
to do a thing yourself.

449
00:23:58,270 --> 00:23:59,362
Well.

450
00:24:00,005 --> 00:24:01,165
You found it okay.

451
00:24:01,239 --> 00:24:02,365
Yes, thank you.

452
00:24:02,441 --> 00:24:03,601
Pleasure to meet you,
Mr. Frost.

453
00:24:03,675 --> 00:24:04,767
And you, sir.

454
00:24:04,843 --> 00:24:06,367
May I present
Caroline Cushing?

455
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:07,503
Miss Cushing.

456
00:24:07,579 --> 00:24:09,672
Hello.
Your house is
very beautiful.

457
00:24:09,748 --> 00:24:10,908
Really. Very romantic.

458
00:24:10,982 --> 00:24:12,074
Well, thank you.

459
00:24:12,150 --> 00:24:13,981
And my producer, John Birt.

460
00:24:14,052 --> 00:24:15,576
Nice to meet you.
How do you do?

461
00:24:15,654 --> 00:24:19,090
This is Mr. Lazar,
and this is Jack Brennan.

462
00:24:19,157 --> 00:24:21,489
Now, Miss Cushing,
would you like
to take a tour,

463
00:24:21,560 --> 00:24:23,858
you know,
maybe stretch your legs
after your long journey?

464
00:24:23,929 --> 00:24:26,591
Yes, please.
I'd love that. Thank you.

465
00:24:27,632 --> 00:24:29,691
Come on in.
This is my office.

466
00:24:29,768 --> 00:24:33,898
Now, this is where Brezhnev
and I had our summit.

467
00:24:33,972 --> 00:24:38,341
Yeah. Brezhnev was there,
and Gromyko there,
Dobrynin there.

468
00:24:39,010 --> 00:24:42,502
We talked for
nine hours straight.

469
00:24:43,715 --> 00:24:47,207
After the meeting,
as a souvenir of the visit,

470
00:24:47,285 --> 00:24:51,551
I remember that we had
a Lincoln specially made.

471
00:24:51,623 --> 00:24:54,820
Dark blue,
cherry wood, leather.

472
00:24:54,893 --> 00:24:57,555
Well, we got inside
for the photographers,

473
00:24:57,629 --> 00:25:01,895
when the next thing you know,
he steps on the gas.

474
00:25:01,967 --> 00:25:06,700
Now, the first rule
of political life is

475
00:25:06,771 --> 00:25:11,208
you never let a president
get behind the wheel
of a car, ever.

476
00:25:11,276 --> 00:25:13,267
I mean, we're not
used to doing anything

477
00:25:13,345 --> 00:25:15,313
for ourselves,
let alone drive.

478
00:25:15,380 --> 00:25:18,577
And the Chairman, Jesus,
the way he put his foot down,

479
00:25:18,650 --> 00:25:21,414
my guess is
the last thing he drove was

480
00:25:21,486 --> 00:25:24,512
a tractor on some
Ukrainian potato farm.

481
00:25:26,424 --> 00:25:27,982
He crashed into curbs.

482
00:25:28,059 --> 00:25:29,549
He went over speed bumps.

483
00:25:29,628 --> 00:25:32,529
He went twice
around my whole estate.

484
00:25:32,597 --> 00:25:37,398
Finally, we ended up
at some remote point
on the coast,

485
00:25:37,469 --> 00:25:40,404
out there
overlooking the sea.

486
00:25:40,472 --> 00:25:44,670
He turns off the gas,
and he talks for two hours

487
00:25:44,743 --> 00:25:48,201
about his favorite subject,
steel mills.

488
00:25:48,280 --> 00:25:51,044
He said, "Mr. President,
most politicians

489
00:25:51,116 --> 00:25:53,812
"have tragedy
in their early lives."

490
00:25:54,719 --> 00:25:58,917
Well, I told him that
I lost two brothers
to tuberculosis.

491
00:25:58,990 --> 00:26:03,984
And he watched his father
die from the cancer
he caught in the steelworks.

492
00:26:04,896 --> 00:26:09,265
He was a sad man
and a noble adversary.

493
00:26:09,935 --> 00:26:12,301
I wouldn't want to
be a Russian leader.

494
00:26:12,804 --> 00:26:15,170
They never know when
they're being taped.

495
00:26:20,779 --> 00:26:22,610
Okay, I guess that's
it then, huh?

496
00:26:22,681 --> 00:26:24,478
Until March.
I look forward to it.

497
00:26:24,549 --> 00:26:26,414
Well, thank you,
Mr. President. So do I.

498
00:26:26,484 --> 00:26:28,111
You know,
it's a funny thing that

499
00:26:28,186 --> 00:26:31,883
I've never been
challenged to a duel before.

500
00:26:31,957 --> 00:26:33,219
I guess that's what this is.

501
00:26:33,291 --> 00:26:35,225
<i>Yeah, well, not really.</i>

502
00:26:36,294 --> 00:26:37,886
Of course it is.

503
00:26:40,031 --> 00:26:41,692
And I like that.

504
00:26:43,001 --> 00:26:46,937
No holds barred, eh?
No holds barred.

505
00:26:50,809 --> 00:26:54,973
Mr. Frost, there's still
the small matter of the...

506
00:26:56,481 --> 00:26:57,743
Of course.

507
00:26:59,184 --> 00:27:01,652
I do beg your pardon.

508
00:27:11,963 --> 00:27:17,230
Right. $200,000.

509
00:27:17,602 --> 00:27:20,469
I do hope that isn't coming
out of your own pocket.

510
00:27:20,538 --> 00:27:23,632
Well, believe me,
sir, I wish my pockets
were that deep.

511
00:27:24,643 --> 00:27:26,338
Made out in the name of?

512
00:27:26,411 --> 00:27:27,537
Irving Paul Lazar.

513
00:27:27,612 --> 00:27:29,443
Richard M. Nixon.

514
00:27:38,456 --> 00:27:39,582
Here you go.

515
00:27:40,892 --> 00:27:42,757
<i>Okay, smile.</i>

516
00:27:44,129 --> 00:27:47,394
There. Now you can put that
in your apartment in New York,

517
00:27:47,465 --> 00:27:51,026
and all your liberal friends
can use it as a dartboard.

518
00:27:51,102 --> 00:27:54,799
Well, actually,
I'm living in Monte Carlo
at the moment.

519
00:27:54,873 --> 00:27:56,272
Really?

520
00:27:56,341 --> 00:27:58,172
Yes. Goodbye, Mr. President.

521
00:27:59,711 --> 00:28:02,646
Hey. Take my advice.

522
00:28:02,714 --> 00:28:04,272
You should marry that woman.

523
00:28:04,349 --> 00:28:07,580
Yes. Lovely, isn't she?

524
00:28:07,652 --> 00:28:10,621
More important than that,
she comes from Monaco.

525
00:28:10,689 --> 00:28:12,714
They pay no taxes there.

526
00:28:14,025 --> 00:28:15,959
Bye-bye.
Goodbye.

527
00:28:24,436 --> 00:28:26,097
I bet you it did.

528
00:28:26,171 --> 00:28:27,195
What?

529
00:28:27,272 --> 00:28:28,671
Come out of his own pocket.

530
00:28:28,740 --> 00:28:30,867
You know, he couldn't
look me in the eye.

531
00:28:30,942 --> 00:28:32,569
Well, I hear
the networks
aren't biting.

532
00:28:32,644 --> 00:28:34,737
Without the networks,
the ad agencies
don't want to know.

533
00:28:34,813 --> 00:28:36,041
So if you ask me,
there's a good chance

534
00:28:36,114 --> 00:28:37,274
this whole thing
may never happen.

535
00:28:37,348 --> 00:28:42,547
Really? So that meeting we just
had might have cost him $200,000?

536
00:28:42,620 --> 00:28:43,712
Correct.

537
00:28:44,589 --> 00:28:48,047
Had I known that,
I would have offered
him a cup of tea.

538
00:28:48,526 --> 00:28:50,926
Say, did you
notice his shoes?

539
00:28:50,995 --> 00:28:52,019
No.

540
00:28:52,097 --> 00:28:55,589
Italian. No laces.
What do you think?

541
00:28:56,401 --> 00:28:58,801
My people tried to get me
to wear a pair like that.

542
00:28:58,870 --> 00:29:01,430
I think a man's shoes
should have laces, sir.

543
00:29:01,639 --> 00:29:02,663
You do?

544
00:29:02,741 --> 00:29:06,302
Yeah. Personally,
I find those Italian
shoes very effeminate.

545
00:29:07,846 --> 00:29:09,438
Yes, quite right.

546
00:29:12,317 --> 00:29:14,444
<i>I'm sorry,</i>
<i>David, but it's a no.</i>

547
00:29:14,519 --> 00:29:16,248
<i>Try to look at it</i>
<i>from our point of view.</i>

548
00:29:16,321 --> 00:29:19,256
<i>Why would an American network</i>
<i>hire a total outsider,</i>

549
00:29:19,324 --> 00:29:22,589
and someone who's already
had his own show canceled,
incidentally?

550
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:24,184
I see. Well, I'm sorry
you feel this way.

551
00:29:24,262 --> 00:29:27,129
Obviously,
I think you're making
a terrible mistake.

552
00:29:29,734 --> 00:29:31,099
NBC.

553
00:29:32,537 --> 00:29:36,598
Well, that's
the networks out,
all of them.

554
00:29:38,176 --> 00:29:40,269
Well, that's the
end of that, then.

555
00:29:45,450 --> 00:29:47,247
I'm sorry, David.

556
00:29:47,919 --> 00:29:49,716
Not so fast.

557
00:29:51,122 --> 00:29:53,647
Where's your
adventurer's spirit?

558
00:29:53,725 --> 00:29:55,693
The idea is
we pay for the program

559
00:29:55,760 --> 00:30:00,788
and syndicate it
ourselves, completely
bypassing the networks.

560
00:30:00,865 --> 00:30:03,459
Just imagine it,
we'd be our own
network for the night.

561
00:30:03,535 --> 00:30:05,435
- Hey, Bob.
- How does that grab you?

562
00:30:05,503 --> 00:30:07,368
Hey, come on in.
David's on the phone.

563
00:30:07,438 --> 00:30:09,269
<i>No, never been
done before.</i>

564
00:30:09,340 --> 00:30:10,932
Historic stuff.

565
00:30:14,312 --> 00:30:17,406
Just think about it, okay?
And call me back.

566
00:30:18,049 --> 00:30:19,539
Yeah?
Yeah.

567
00:30:19,617 --> 00:30:22,643
David, I'd like you
to meet Jim Reston
and Bob Zelnick,

568
00:30:22,720 --> 00:30:23,914
our two prospective
corner men.

569
00:30:23,988 --> 00:30:25,080
Delighted to meet you.

570
00:30:25,156 --> 00:30:26,953
Come on in.
Make yourselves at home.

571
00:30:27,025 --> 00:30:28,356
Bob's been
Washington correspondent

572
00:30:28,426 --> 00:30:29,723
for Public Radio
for the past 10 years.

573
00:30:29,794 --> 00:30:31,989
Moving to ABC
in the new year.

574
00:30:32,063 --> 00:30:33,394
The general feeling, David,

575
00:30:33,464 --> 00:30:37,264
is that I have been
wasting my matinee idol
looks on radio.

576
00:30:37,902 --> 00:30:39,893
Jim here teaches
at the University
of North Carolina

577
00:30:39,971 --> 00:30:43,805
and is writing a book
about the criminal
dishonesty, corruption,

578
00:30:44,509 --> 00:30:46,943
paranoia and abuses of
power of Richard Nixon.

579
00:30:47,011 --> 00:30:48,478
Second on the subject.

580
00:30:48,546 --> 00:30:49,604
Fourth.

581
00:30:49,681 --> 00:30:51,740
Well, delighted to
have you both aboard.

582
00:30:51,816 --> 00:30:54,250
Actually, before I sign on,
I would like to hear

583
00:30:54,319 --> 00:30:57,186
what you were
hoping to achieve
with this interview.

584
00:30:57,789 --> 00:30:59,780
What I want to achieve?

585
00:30:59,858 --> 00:31:01,120
Yeah.

586
00:31:01,593 --> 00:31:05,290
Jim, well,
I've secured 12 taping days.

587
00:31:05,363 --> 00:31:07,297
That's close to 30 hours

588
00:31:07,365 --> 00:31:09,560
with the most compelling
and controversial politician

589
00:31:09,634 --> 00:31:11,397
of our times.

590
00:31:11,469 --> 00:31:12,936
Isn't that enough?

591
00:31:14,839 --> 00:31:16,170
Well, not for me.

592
00:31:17,508 --> 00:31:20,841
Look, I'd be giving up
a year of my life.
I'm leaving my family

593
00:31:20,912 --> 00:31:23,574
to work on
a subject matter
that means more

594
00:31:23,648 --> 00:31:25,343
than you can
probably imagine,

595
00:31:25,416 --> 00:31:26,508
and the idea
of doing all that

596
00:31:26,584 --> 00:31:30,020
without achieving what
I want to, personally,

597
00:31:30,088 --> 00:31:31,851
would be unthinkable to me.

598
00:31:31,923 --> 00:31:33,151
<i>No, all right.</i>

599
00:31:33,892 --> 00:31:36,588
Well, what is it that
you want to achieve?

600
00:31:42,233 --> 00:31:45,202
I'd like to
give Richard Nixon
the trial he never had.

601
00:31:45,270 --> 00:31:48,535
Of course,
we'll be asking
difficult questions.

602
00:31:48,606 --> 00:31:50,267
Difficult questions.

603
00:31:51,209 --> 00:31:53,404
The man lost 21,000 Americans

604
00:31:53,478 --> 00:31:55,912
and a million Indo-Chinese
during his administration.

605
00:31:55,980 --> 00:31:58,778
He only escaped jail
because of Ford's pardon.

606
00:31:58,850 --> 00:32:02,149
Yes, but equally,
going after him
in some knee-jerk way,

607
00:32:02,220 --> 00:32:05,747
you know, assuming
he's a terrible guy,

608
00:32:05,823 --> 00:32:09,520
wouldn't that only create
more sympathy for him
than anything else?

609
00:32:09,594 --> 00:32:11,061
You know...

610
00:32:13,264 --> 00:32:15,061
Right now,
I submit it's impossible

611
00:32:15,133 --> 00:32:18,625
to feel anything
close to sympathy
for Richard Nixon.

612
00:32:18,703 --> 00:32:20,830
He devalued the presidency,

613
00:32:20,905 --> 00:32:24,500
and he left the country
that elected him in trauma.

614
00:32:25,643 --> 00:32:29,340
The American people
need a conviction,
pure and simple.

615
00:32:29,414 --> 00:32:32,110
The integrity of
our political system,

616
00:32:32,183 --> 00:32:38,019
of democracy as an idea,
entirely depends on it.

617
00:32:38,089 --> 00:32:40,387
And if in years to come,
people look back

618
00:32:40,458 --> 00:32:41,857
and say it was
in this interview

619
00:32:41,926 --> 00:32:43,518
that Richard Nixon
exonerated himself,

620
00:32:43,594 --> 00:32:45,789
that would be
the worst crime of all.

621
00:32:55,506 --> 00:32:58,566
Did you know that
Mike Wallace is doing
a piece on this?

622
00:33:00,511 --> 00:33:03,207
And that in the bars around
Capitol Hill and Georgetown

623
00:33:03,281 --> 00:33:05,044
this entire project is a joke?

624
00:33:05,116 --> 00:33:07,778
<i>Come on.
Jim, come on.</i>

625
00:33:07,852 --> 00:33:10,184
Thanks for that, Jim.

626
00:33:11,222 --> 00:33:13,554
Could you give us
a couple of minutes?

627
00:33:20,798 --> 00:33:22,288
You're unbelievable.
I'm sorry, Bob.

628
00:33:22,367 --> 00:33:24,597
You know, Jim,
I went way out
on a limb for you.

629
00:33:24,669 --> 00:33:26,261
I mean, some of us
actually want this job.

630
00:33:26,337 --> 00:33:27,827
I want it, too,
if it's done right.

631
00:33:27,905 --> 00:33:29,702
Well, how do you know
they're not
gonna do it right?

632
00:33:29,774 --> 00:33:31,002
Little Lord Fauntleroy
in there?

633
00:33:31,075 --> 00:33:32,269
Sympathy for Richard Nixon?

634
00:33:32,343 --> 00:33:33,970
What the...
He's full of shit, man!

635
00:33:34,045 --> 00:33:35,569
How do you know that?

636
00:33:37,782 --> 00:33:40,751
Is Mike Wallace
doing a piece on this?

637
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:43,044
Apparently.

638
00:33:43,121 --> 00:33:44,748
Why didn't you tell me?

639
00:33:45,490 --> 00:33:46,889
It isn't relevant.

640
00:33:47,992 --> 00:33:51,723
What's the angle?
"British talk show host,

641
00:33:52,497 --> 00:33:56,228
"good with actresses,
not so good with
stonewalling presidents."

642
00:33:56,534 --> 00:33:58,331
That's the general idea, yeah.

643
00:33:58,403 --> 00:33:59,597
Right.

644
00:34:00,838 --> 00:34:03,568
It's hard not to feel
a little insulted by that.

645
00:34:05,276 --> 00:34:07,744
Well, Bob's obviously a pro.

646
00:34:07,812 --> 00:34:09,006
What are we gonna
do about Reston?

647
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:10,638
Well, the man's an idiot.
He's overemotional.

648
00:34:10,715 --> 00:34:11,977
Send him home.

649
00:34:13,384 --> 00:34:15,352
Well, I think
he should stay.
Why?

650
00:34:15,420 --> 00:34:18,719
I liked his passion.

651
00:34:18,790 --> 00:34:20,781
He will drive us
all bloody mad.

652
00:34:21,325 --> 00:34:24,055
Well, maybe, but sometimes
being out of your comfort zone

653
00:34:24,128 --> 00:34:26,790
is a good thing, I'm told.

654
00:34:27,832 --> 00:34:29,094
He stays.

655
00:34:39,710 --> 00:34:43,806
<i>I took my seat</i>
<i>next to Mrs. Mao</i>
<i>at the banquet table.</i>

656
00:34:44,449 --> 00:34:49,148
<i>Now, one of the challenges</i>
<i>of life as a president</i>

657
00:34:49,854 --> 00:34:56,783
<i>is the endless round</i>
<i>of cocktail parties,</i>
<i>social engagements, banquets.</i>

658
00:34:57,528 --> 00:34:59,519
<i>And people who</i>
<i>know me would tell you</i>

659
00:34:59,597 --> 00:35:03,829
<i>that small talk is not one of</i>
<i>my strong suits, either. No.</i>

660
00:35:04,502 --> 00:35:07,596
<i>Particularly not in Mandarin.</i>

661
00:35:10,608 --> 00:35:15,602
<i>So Mrs. Mao and I,</i>
<i>we just, well, you know,</i>
<i>stared at one another.</i>

662
00:35:16,747 --> 00:35:21,047
<i>And then across the table,</i>
<i>Mrs. Nixon and</i>
<i>Chairman Mao himself, well,</i>

663
00:35:21,886 --> 00:35:24,252
<i>they stared</i>
<i>at one another, too.</i>

664
00:35:24,322 --> 00:35:27,189
<i>And then further down,</i>
<i>Dr. Kissinger</i>

665
00:35:27,258 --> 00:35:30,091
<i>and their</i>
<i>foreign minister, well,</i>

666
00:35:30,595 --> 00:35:33,621
<i>you're getting</i>
<i>the picture now.</i>

667
00:35:38,302 --> 00:35:40,270
I can't stand it, Jack!

668
00:35:41,572 --> 00:35:46,737
Reducing the presidency
to a series
of banal anecdotes.

669
00:35:46,911 --> 00:35:49,744
I feel like
a circus animal
doing tricks.

670
00:35:49,947 --> 00:35:51,710
And I thought
I made it clear!

671
00:35:51,782 --> 00:35:56,310
I didn't want to take
any questions
on Watergate, damn it!

672
00:35:57,755 --> 00:36:00,121
Soon as it came
to question time,

673
00:36:00,191 --> 00:36:04,821
all those sons of bitches
ever want to hear about
is Watergate!

674
00:36:04,929 --> 00:36:09,389
It's as if all
my other achievements
have ceased to exist.

675
00:36:09,467 --> 00:36:10,729
Well, sir, you're
gonna get a chance

676
00:36:10,801 --> 00:36:12,098
to talk about them
sooner than you think.

677
00:36:12,170 --> 00:36:13,831
Yeah? How?

678
00:36:13,905 --> 00:36:16,305
Frost got there.
He got the money.

679
00:36:17,608 --> 00:36:19,007
What?

680
00:36:19,076 --> 00:36:20,543
I understand
most of it's borrowed,

681
00:36:20,611 --> 00:36:22,374
that his friends
have bailed him out.

682
00:36:22,446 --> 00:36:24,641
But the point is,
we start taping
at the end of March.

683
00:36:24,715 --> 00:36:27,445
Really? Now, that's terrific.

684
00:36:27,518 --> 00:36:29,281
How much time is
devoted to Watergate?

685
00:36:29,353 --> 00:36:32,220
25%. Just one of
four 90-minute shows.

686
00:36:32,290 --> 00:36:34,281
What are the other
three divided into?

687
00:36:34,358 --> 00:36:36,383
Domestic Affairs,
Foreign Policy,

688
00:36:36,460 --> 00:36:37,518
and Nixon the Man.

689
00:36:37,595 --> 00:36:38,584
"Nixon the Man"?

