00:59:30,099 --> 00:59:33,432
in that
heart-to-heart you had
with Henry Kissinger.

1155
00:59:33,502 --> 00:59:37,131
Was that perhaps
the most emotional moment
of your career?

1156
00:59:37,606 --> 00:59:39,198
- Good, good.
<i>- Yes.</i>

1157
00:59:39,942 --> 00:59:45,244
I would say it was
about as emotional
a moment as I've ever had.

1158
00:59:47,416 --> 00:59:49,543
Except, well,
you know,
it's hard to say

1159
00:59:49,618 --> 00:59:51,711
what is the most
emotional moment,

1160
00:59:51,787 --> 00:59:54,381
because each is different.

1161
00:59:54,823 --> 00:59:57,917
<i>I remember the day</i>
<i>Eisenhower died.</i>

1162
00:59:57,993 --> 00:59:59,290
For God's sake.

1163
00:59:59,361 --> 01:00:03,627
<i>And the day I walked</i>
<i>my eldest daughter</i>
<i>Tricia down the aisle.</i>

1164
01:00:03,699 --> 01:00:06,395
And the day during
the impeachment hearings

1165
01:00:06,468 --> 01:00:10,097
when Julie,
that's my youngest,
she came into my office,

1166
01:00:10,172 --> 01:00:14,666
she threw her arms around me,
she kissed me.
She cried, you know?

1167
01:00:14,743 --> 01:00:17,644
And she so seldom cries.

1168
01:00:17,846 --> 01:00:20,178
<i>She said, "Daddy, you're</i>
<i>the finest man I know. "</i>

1169
01:00:20,249 --> 01:00:22,240
"Daddy, you're
the finest man I know"?

1170
01:00:22,718 --> 01:00:26,210
"And whatever you do,
I will support you.

1171
01:00:27,289 --> 01:00:31,623
"You just gotta
go through the fire,
you know, a little longer."

1172
01:00:33,996 --> 01:00:35,759
This is beautiful.

1173
01:00:35,831 --> 01:00:38,994
So Kissinger and I were
in the Lincoln Sitting Room,

1174
01:00:39,067 --> 01:00:42,059
and together we began
to reminisce

1175
01:00:42,137 --> 01:00:45,971
about some of
the great decisions that
we'd participated in.

1176
01:00:46,041 --> 01:00:49,238
There was China,
the Soviet Union,

1177
01:00:49,311 --> 01:00:51,836
the peace settlement
in Vietnam.

1178
01:00:51,914 --> 01:00:55,941
<i>Now, let me</i>
<i>tell you something that</i>
<i>I never told anybody.</i>

1179
01:00:56,018 --> 01:01:00,455
Whenever I have had
a really tough
decision to make...

1180
01:01:00,789 --> 01:01:03,553
Now, we were in
the Lincoln Sitting Room
at that time.

1181
01:01:03,625 --> 01:01:07,322
I have come into this room
for the purpose of praying.

1182
01:01:08,363 --> 01:01:12,231
"Now, Henry,
I'm a Quaker.
You're a Jew.

1183
01:01:12,301 --> 01:01:14,269
"Neither of us is
particularly orthodox,

1184
01:01:14,336 --> 01:01:17,362
"but I'd like to think
that each of us
in our own way

1185
01:01:17,439 --> 01:01:20,431
"has a deep
religious sensitivity.

1186
01:01:20,509 --> 01:01:25,606
"So if you don't mind,
could we just have a moment
of silent prayer?"

1187
01:01:25,681 --> 01:01:29,913
So we knelt down.
Now, this was in front
of that table where

1188
01:01:29,985 --> 01:01:34,149
Lincoln signed
the Emancipation
Proclamation.

1189
01:01:34,223 --> 01:01:37,659
And then after a few moments,
we both got up again,
and Henry says...

1190
01:01:37,759 --> 01:01:39,317
Is there... I'm sorry.

1191
01:01:39,461 --> 01:01:40,621
Is there a problem?

1192
01:01:40,696 --> 01:01:41,720
That's time.

1193
01:01:42,297 --> 01:01:44,424
We're over two hours.

1194
01:01:44,500 --> 01:01:46,593
Really? So soon?

1195
01:01:47,302 --> 01:01:50,271
Well, Mr. President,
I gather our time is up.

1196
01:01:50,472 --> 01:01:52,269
Gee, now, that's a pity.

1197
01:01:52,341 --> 01:01:54,832
You know,
I was beginning
to enjoy that.

1198
01:01:58,814 --> 01:02:01,180
That was terrific,
both of you.

1199
01:02:01,250 --> 01:02:02,615
We're getting some
great material.

1200
01:02:02,684 --> 01:02:04,049
You know,
it's so funny, too,

1201
01:02:04,119 --> 01:02:07,555
because I was expecting
questions on Vietnam.

1202
01:02:07,623 --> 01:02:10,114
And we prepared for that,
hadn't we, Jack?

1203
01:02:10,192 --> 01:02:11,591
Yes, so did I.

1204
01:02:11,660 --> 01:02:14,788
I guess we
just got caught up,
you know, reminiscing.

1205
01:02:14,863 --> 01:02:15,887
Indeed.

1206
01:02:15,964 --> 01:02:18,228
So, day after tomorrow,
10:00, right?

1207
01:02:18,300 --> 01:02:19,392
Yes, indeed.

1208
01:02:19,468 --> 01:02:21,163
I look forward to it.
Bye-bye.

1209
01:02:28,644 --> 01:02:30,703
There's no need
to say anything.

1210
01:02:37,286 --> 01:02:39,413
- Mr. President!
- Mr. President!

1211
01:02:42,491 --> 01:02:43,753
<i>Mr. President!</i>

1212
01:02:43,825 --> 01:02:45,156
<i>Mr. President, please!</i>

1213
01:02:46,161 --> 01:02:47,389
What are you
gonna tell him?

1214
01:02:47,462 --> 01:02:49,157
I'm gonna tell him
he's gotta get involved.

1215
01:02:49,231 --> 01:02:51,062
He's gotta be able
to shut him up.
Shh.

1216
01:02:51,133 --> 01:02:54,159
David, we have some
fundamental problems in
our approach that I think...

1217
01:02:54,236 --> 01:02:55,635
Don't worry, Bob.
I'm on it.

1218
01:02:55,704 --> 01:02:56,728
We can use some of
the Kissinger stuff.

1219
01:02:56,805 --> 01:02:58,534
Yeah, but we need
to discuss it sooner
rather than later...

1220
01:02:58,607 --> 01:02:59,972
Look,
I'm disappointed, too.

1221
01:03:00,042 --> 01:03:02,772
But I wonder,
could we possibly spare
the post-mortem for now?

1222
01:03:02,844 --> 01:03:04,903
I don't mean to minimize it.
It's just I've got to
get back to LA

1223
01:03:04,980 --> 01:03:06,379
to meet some people
from Weed Eater.

1224
01:03:06,448 --> 01:03:08,279
Thanks, everyone!
Great work!

1225
01:03:08,350 --> 01:03:10,545
Marv, Lloyd, great day.
Bye, David.

1226
01:03:10,619 --> 01:03:13,486
I'll see you soon.
God bless!

1227
01:03:16,525 --> 01:03:18,925
What the hell
is Weed Eater?

1228
01:03:19,227 --> 01:03:21,457
It's a horticultural
mechanism.

1229
01:03:21,530 --> 01:03:22,554
One of our sponsors.

1230
01:03:22,631 --> 01:03:23,996
What happened to Xerox?

1231
01:03:24,066 --> 01:03:26,330
What about
General Motors
or IBM?

1232
01:03:26,401 --> 01:03:29,461
I gather that not all of
the blue-chip accounts
came through.

1233
01:03:29,538 --> 01:03:31,733
We do have Alpo.

1234
01:03:31,807 --> 01:03:33,206
Dog food?

1235
01:03:33,275 --> 01:03:35,641
Wait, John.
We're already taping.

1236
01:03:36,144 --> 01:03:37,839
So we're close, right?
We're very close?

1237
01:03:37,913 --> 01:03:39,346
That's probably a question
you should ask David.

1238
01:03:39,414 --> 01:03:41,279
Are we close, John?

1239
01:03:44,186 --> 01:03:46,279
I believe we're at 30%.

1240
01:03:47,055 --> 01:03:48,545
To go? Or 30% sold?

1241
01:03:48,624 --> 01:03:51,320
Again, that's probably
a question you should...

1242
01:03:52,394 --> 01:03:53,986
Sold, 30% sold.

1243
01:03:54,696 --> 01:03:56,220
Jesus...

1244
01:03:56,365 --> 01:03:57,923
I thought
we were practically
fully financed.

1245
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:01,128
We were. But the financing
was always conditional
on advertising sales,

1246
01:04:01,203 --> 01:04:02,898
and no one predicted
that they'd fall apart
like this.

1247
01:04:02,971 --> 01:04:04,871
Well, why have
they fallen apart?
Based on what?

1248
01:04:04,940 --> 01:04:07,738
Credibility of the project.
What else are advertising
sales based on?

1249
01:04:07,809 --> 01:04:09,970
Listen,
I understand your concern.

1250
01:04:10,045 --> 01:04:13,242
But could I ask you
to go a little easier on David
over the next couple of days,

1251
01:04:13,315 --> 01:04:15,783
bearing in mind
the extraordinary pressure
that he's under?

1252
01:04:15,851 --> 01:04:19,343
'Cause at the moment,
he's effectively paying
for all this himself.

1253
01:04:19,421 --> 01:04:23,084
So he's in it
for a lot more than
just his reputation.

1254
01:04:23,425 --> 01:04:24,722
And we're not?

1255
01:04:31,800 --> 01:04:35,395
<i>You seemed</i>
<i>very confident last time.</i>

1256
01:04:35,470 --> 01:04:38,405
<i>I don't understand.</i>
<i>Why this sudden</i>
<i>change of heart?</i>

1257
01:04:38,473 --> 01:04:41,033
All right,
this is just madness.
It's Richard Nixon.

1258
01:04:41,109 --> 01:04:45,341
These interviews
will do mid-30s
audience share, minimum.

1259
01:04:45,414 --> 01:04:52,047
Jimmy! Yes.
Yes, back again, like
the proverbial bad penny.

1260
01:04:52,120 --> 01:04:53,678
Look, I hate to do
this to a friend,

1261
01:04:53,755 --> 01:04:56,986
and I know you're already in
for more than I asked for,

1262
01:04:57,059 --> 01:05:00,495
but I need you to dig
a little deeper.

1263
01:05:02,030 --> 01:05:04,191
I'm right up against it now.

1264
01:05:07,769 --> 01:05:10,966
So, I had
a chance to review
yesterday's tapes.

1265
01:05:11,039 --> 01:05:12,267
And?

1266
01:05:12,340 --> 01:05:16,367
Honestly?
Far too soft, David.

1267
01:05:16,445 --> 01:05:18,538
Go on. Beat me, John.
Beat me with a stick.

1268
01:05:18,613 --> 01:05:21,605
Look. No, I'm serious.

1269
01:05:21,683 --> 01:05:24,083
You have got to make it
more uncomfortable for him.

1270
01:05:24,152 --> 01:05:26,882
You can start by
sitting forward.
You've gotta attack more.

1271
01:05:26,955 --> 01:05:28,547
If he starts
tailing off, bang,

1272
01:05:28,623 --> 01:05:30,022
jump in with
another question.

1273
01:05:30,092 --> 01:05:32,117
Don't trade
generalizations.

1274
01:05:32,194 --> 01:05:33,218
Be specific.

1275
01:05:33,295 --> 01:05:36,389
And above all, don't let
him give these self-serving,
23-minute homilies.

1276
01:05:36,465 --> 01:05:37,489
Right.
And keep your distance

1277
01:05:37,566 --> 01:05:38,828
before the tape
starts running.

1278
01:05:38,900 --> 01:05:40,197
He was toying
with you yesterday.

1279
01:05:40,268 --> 01:05:42,532
All that shit about <i>Ben-Hur</i>
and struggling to raise
the money.

1280
01:05:42,604 --> 01:05:46,665
Those are mind games.
Don't engage.

1281
01:05:46,742 --> 01:05:50,200
Never forget,
you are in there
with a major operator.

1282
01:05:51,446 --> 01:05:52,845
Got it.

1283
01:06:00,122 --> 01:06:01,146
Ah.

1284
01:06:01,990 --> 01:06:03,924
The Grand Inquisitor!

1285
01:06:05,093 --> 01:06:07,527
No, just your friendly
neighborhood confidant.

1286
01:06:12,400 --> 01:06:14,493
It's okay.
We just blew a bulb.

1287
01:06:15,270 --> 01:06:17,761
<i>This is why I got all these
Secret Service guys around.</i>

1288
01:06:17,839 --> 01:06:19,204
There's nothing
to worry about.

1289
01:06:19,274 --> 01:06:22,641
As a president, you get
used to this kind of stuff.

1290
01:06:22,811 --> 01:06:26,303
<i>Ed, we gotta get in here and
change out this 750, ASAP.</i>

1291
01:06:31,753 --> 01:06:33,414
- Focus, sir.
- Yeah.

1292
01:06:35,991 --> 01:06:39,620
Okay, we are back.
Okay, take it
on my count.

1293
01:06:40,462 --> 01:06:43,397
Okay, stand by
to roll tape.
30 seconds.

1294
01:06:43,698 --> 01:06:44,926
<i>Settling.</i>

1295
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:46,661
You have a pleasant
evening last night?

1296
01:06:46,735 --> 01:06:48,327
Yes, thank you.

1297
01:06:56,478 --> 01:06:58,776
Did you do
any fornicating?

1298
01:06:59,047 --> 01:07:02,073
David, we're starting
with camera two in four,

1299
01:07:03,218 --> 01:07:05,413
Three, two and...

1300
01:07:10,025 --> 01:07:13,256
Mr. President, you came
to office promising peace,

1301
01:07:13,328 --> 01:07:15,319
but no sooner did you
get into the White House

1302
01:07:15,397 --> 01:07:19,834
than US involvement in Vietnam
deepened and the war was prolonged

1303
01:07:19,901 --> 01:07:21,493
with calamitous
consequences.

1304
01:07:21,570 --> 01:07:25,028
Did you feel that you'd betrayed
the people that had elected you?

1305
01:07:25,106 --> 01:07:28,872
Well, Vietnam
was not my war.

1306
01:07:28,944 --> 01:07:30,605
It was my inheritance.

1307
01:07:30,679 --> 01:07:32,544
<i>And it looked to me...</i>
Jump in.

1308
01:07:32,614 --> 01:07:35,640
...as if the reason
for our being there

1309
01:07:35,717 --> 01:07:40,416
had perhaps not been adequately
understood by the American people.

1310
01:07:40,822 --> 01:07:42,847
It seemed to me
they hadn't realized

1311
01:07:42,924 --> 01:07:48,123
how important a test this
was of American credibility.

1312
01:07:48,830 --> 01:07:50,855
The whole world
was watching to see

1313
01:07:50,932 --> 01:07:53,958
if we have the character
to see it through.

1314
01:07:54,035 --> 01:07:56,799
Now, look, I could have bugged out.
I could have.

1315
01:07:56,872 --> 01:07:59,534
I could have blamed it
on my predecessors.

1316
01:07:59,608 --> 01:08:02,099
I could have pulled the
troops out of Vietnam early,

1317
01:08:02,177 --> 01:08:04,509
and very possibly,
I would have won

1318
01:08:04,579 --> 01:08:07,810
some Scandinavian peace prize
into the bargain.

1319
01:08:07,883 --> 01:08:09,544
But I believed
in the cause.

1320
01:08:09,618 --> 01:08:14,954
And sometimes, you know, what you
believe in, it's the harder path.

1321
01:08:15,023 --> 01:08:19,858
You might even say that I was the
last casualty of the Vietnam War.

1322
01:08:19,928 --> 01:08:22,692
Yeah, tell that
to the paraplegics.

1323
01:08:22,797 --> 01:08:24,128
Come on, David,
Cambodia.

1324
01:08:24,199 --> 01:08:27,362
And Cambodia? An invasion which
everybody advised you against.

1325
01:08:27,435 --> 01:08:30,461
All the CIA
and Pentagon intelligence
suggested it would fail.

1326
01:08:30,538 --> 01:08:31,630
So why did you do it?

1327
01:08:31,706 --> 01:08:32,764
Well, first of all,

1328
01:08:32,841 --> 01:08:39,269
as a result of
our incursion into Cambodia,
we picked up 22,000 rifles,

1329
01:08:39,347 --> 01:08:43,841
15 million rounds
of ammunition,
150,000 rockets, mortars.

1330
01:08:43,919 --> 01:08:46,149
That's all belonging
to the North Vietnamese,

1331
01:08:46,221 --> 01:08:49,247
which would only otherwise
have been directed

1332
01:08:49,324 --> 01:08:51,451
right onto
American soldiers.

1333
01:08:51,526 --> 01:08:54,791
But one of
the principal justifications
you gave for the incursion

1334
01:08:54,863 --> 01:08:56,524
was the supposed
existence of

1335
01:08:56,598 --> 01:09:01,501
the "headquarters of
the entire Communist military
operation in South Vietnam,"

1336
01:09:01,569 --> 01:09:05,335
a sort of "bamboo Pentagon"
which proved
not to exist at all.

1337
01:09:05,407 --> 01:09:07,068
No, no. Wait a minute
there. No, I was...
And by sending...

1338
01:09:07,142 --> 01:09:10,373
And by sending B-52s
to carpet bomb a country,

1339
01:09:10,445 --> 01:09:13,005
wiping out
whole civilian areas,

1340
01:09:13,081 --> 01:09:16,107
you end up radicalizing
a once moderate people,

1341
01:09:16,184 --> 01:09:18,778
uniting them in
anti-American sentiment

1342
01:09:18,920 --> 01:09:21,514
<i>and creating a monster</i>
<i>in the Khmer Rouge</i>

1343
01:09:21,589 --> 01:09:22,920
<i>that would lead</i>
<i>to civil war...</i>

1344
01:09:22,991 --> 01:09:24,652
All right!
...<i>and genocide.</i>

1345
01:09:24,793 --> 01:09:26,260
Yes, good, good, good.
There it is.

1346
01:09:26,328 --> 01:09:27,488
Okay, run VT.

1347
01:09:27,562 --> 01:09:28,551
Roll tape.

1348
01:10:25,186 --> 01:10:26,414
Well, sir,
I'm sure you'd agree,

1349
01:10:26,488 --> 01:10:28,547
some pretty
stirring images there.

1350
01:10:28,623 --> 01:10:34,391
Look, it was never US policy
to kill civilians.
That's the enemy's way.

1351
01:10:34,462 --> 01:10:35,451
Well, I'm not suggesting...

1352
01:10:35,530 --> 01:10:36,588
And if you're
asking the question

1353
01:10:36,664 --> 01:10:40,760
do I regret the casualties
on both sides in the war,
yeah, sure, of course I do.

1354
01:10:40,835 --> 01:10:42,894
Let me tell you something.
It can just wear you down.

1355
01:10:42,971 --> 01:10:44,905
Well, all right, sir,
when you are faced
with someone who...

1356
01:10:44,973 --> 01:10:47,032
But whenever
I have had my doubts,

1357
01:10:47,108 --> 01:10:49,235
I remembered
the construction worker
in Philadelphia,

1358
01:10:49,310 --> 01:10:50,538
because he came up to me

1359
01:10:50,612 --> 01:10:54,173
and he said, "Sir,
I got only one criticism
of that Cambodia thing.

1360
01:10:54,249 --> 01:10:55,978
"If you'd gone in earlier,

1361
01:10:56,051 --> 01:10:57,814
"you might have
captured the gun

1362
01:10:57,886 --> 01:10:59,911
"that killed my boy
three months ago."

1363
01:10:59,988 --> 01:11:02,980
So you're asking me,
do I regret
going into Cambodia?

1364
01:11:03,058 --> 01:11:05,322
No! I don't.
You know what?

1365
01:11:05,393 --> 01:11:08,453
I wish I'd gone in
sooner and harder.

1366
01:11:08,530 --> 01:11:09,588
- Got him.
- Safe!

1367
01:11:16,071 --> 01:11:20,940
It was horrifying.
It was horrifying.
And he was so confident.

1368
01:11:23,945 --> 01:11:26,379
<i>What are you gonna say
about Watergate?</i>

1369
01:11:26,714 --> 01:11:30,013
Sorry, boys,
just all talked out,
you know?

1370
01:11:36,758 --> 01:11:38,157
Better?

1371
01:11:41,763 --> 01:11:43,856
It was.
Unquestionably better.

1372
01:11:49,304 --> 01:11:50,532
What's next?

1373
01:11:51,172 --> 01:11:52,400
Foreign policy.

1374
01:11:54,943 --> 01:12:00,006
Great. Russia, China,
the big power stuff.

1375
01:12:00,081 --> 01:12:02,379
Yeah, so?

1376
01:12:02,450 --> 01:12:04,213
So if he beats him up
like that on Vietnam,

1377
01:12:04,285 --> 01:12:07,186
imagine what he's gonna do
with his real achievements.

1378
01:12:09,791 --> 01:12:12,157
It ain't gonna be pretty.

1379
01:12:12,227 --> 01:12:14,957
The answer was
grow by six inches.

1380
01:12:15,029 --> 01:12:17,930
It was agony to watch.

1381
01:12:18,700 --> 01:12:21,601
